each i$100 of tax\nable valuation for fcchool and gen\neral purposes and 8 bents to pay\ninterest on the State certificates\nol indebtedness to the school fund,\na perpetual debt fastened bn tha\npeople by Democrats. The gov\nernor can;, however, recommend\nthat all taxable property Ibe re\nturned for taxation at Jits real\nvalue, and that the rate of tax\nation be so fixed us to produce\nsufficient revenue to meet the ex\npenses of bconoro'cally conducted\nstate and couaty government.\nThe rate frnay foe deduced 'by the\nlegislature, but cannot be in\ncreased. If ail property (subject 'to\ntaxation could be (returned Jit its\nreal or cash value a rate ol 10c\nwill produce more revenue than\nthe present rate produces from\ntaxable values dishonestly, un\nfairly and unequally returned.\nAn honest farmer who returns\nhis land oir taxation tit 'its real\nvalue pays proportionately more\nin taxes than his Uishonest neigh\nbor who puts a fictitious valuation\non his land. It is the idea of Gov.\nHadley that alir eal testate and\nother property should be listed at\nits real, honest value hi money,\nand that ar ate of taxation should\nbe established bn that Valuation,\nnot on an arbitrary or fictitious\nvaluation. In fchat way every tax\npayer would have to pay his just\nproportion of taxes. The honest\ntax-payer would not h'avo to make\nup for tine dishonesty 'of fcrthertax\npayers. Anything wrong about\nthat?\nCHEAP POLITICS AND EMIGRA\nTION. The Cheap tfohn Democratic pol\niticians are now trying to show\nthat Democratic state officials are\ncheaper than Republican state\nofficials. The people discovered\nthat \"years ago and need not be\nreminded of' it now. Theg overn\nment ol Missouri had been so\ncheap, so slow, fco inefficient, and\nso discouraging prior to .1904 that\n.hnjhdreds, oX thousands pjt gopd\n'farmers, mechanics and business\n,men went to Oklahoma, Texas and\nthe Northwest to' Uve! There has\nbeen very 'little, emigration from\nMissouri wince Republicans took\nup the reins of government. Sinoa\nthe election of Gov. Hadley a tide\nof immigration lina set In. And,\nunless Democratic Influences stop\nthe work of the Immigration Com\nmissioners), that tide will rise high\nand fill up the state in u few\nyears.\nThe Sudden death of Chief Jus\ntice VJas. D. Fox, of the supreme\ncourt, was a shock to the people\nof Jefferson City, where he was\npersonally popular. Ho wws genial\nand kind, always ready for a\npleasant moment with a friend,\nand devoid of affectation of any\nkind. Though a Democrat of the\nold school nnd a devoted parti-,\nsan, \"he was agreeable to his .Re\npublican friends, and acquaint\nances, lievcr offending by par\ntisan remarks. It watt his intention\nto become a candidate for the\nDemocratic nomination for gov\nernor in 1912. Re was elected a\nmember of the supreme court In\n1902 for a term of ten years.\nJudge Henry S. Caulfield, who\nwas appointed (by Gov. (Hadley a\nmember of the St. 'Louis Court of\nAppeals to Succeed Judgo Goodc,\na Democrat, has taken his place on\nthat bench, Und lias .been nominat\ned by iifc Republicans M the dis\ntrict over which that court has\njurisdiction for the Unexpired term\nof Judgo 'Goodel two years from\nJanuary, 1911. His public record\ncommended Judge Caulfield to the\nfavor of Gov. Hadley, who imme\ndiately appoSnted (him ito Che va\ncancy when ho accepted the res\nignation oi Judge Goode. No man\ncan make a mistake by voting for\nJudge Caulfield.\nMissouri Fight for Reform, Under Hadley,\nCompared to Present New York Situation\nHo donounccd the Democratic party In Now York, as an\nunholy alliance botweon Wall street and Tammany Hall,\"\nand attacked the Democratic party In Missouri by calling it\ntho party \"that represents tho special interests and special\nprlvilodgcs.\"\n\"Gov. Hadley,\" ho continued, \"has represented that\nkind of party loyalty In which 1 most bclolvo; tho kind of\nlayalty to the party which flads expression by seeing to it\nthat that party is tho most loyal servant of tho people as a\nwhole. And so I am glad, indeed, to cotno hero to-night to\nspeak for him because I think that tho conditions of your\nlight here are substantially akin to tho conditions of the fight\nwo aro making in New York State, in my own state.\n\"And as it is in New York so it is -hero in Missouri, the\ngenuine party of the poople, the party that stands for all tho\npeople is the Republican party, and tho pirty of reaction\nand of Bourbonlsm, the party thut represents the apodal\nprivilege, Is the party that arrogates to itself forsooth, the\nname of the Democracy.\"\nExtract From Roosevelt's Coliseum Speech\n\"Shannon's Rabbits\" in Kansas\nCitv and \"Butler's Indians\" In Gt.\nLouis were powerful allies of the session in connection with the de\nMETHODIST CHURCH NOTES.\nSunday school at 0:45 a. m..\nJoin the procession and o to\nSunday school Sunday, and see\nwhat is going on.\nPreaching at 11 a. m.\nJunior League at 2:30 p. m.\nSenior League at 6:45 p. m.\nPreaching at 7:30 p. m.\nPrayer meeting Wednesday at\n7:30 p. m.\nThe public is cordially invited to\nthe services of this church.\nThe League will hold a business\nDemocratic party a few years ago.\nButler is now too old for poli\ntics and his \"Indians\" have been\nput out of business by a Republi\ncan election board. Shannon Is\nnow the Democratic state chair\nman, but his \"Rabbits\" have sought\nvotional Services Sunday.\nLeaguers be on time.\nLA tho\nThe Rev. Rockwell Smith, ID. D\nmissionary to Brazil, will 'speak\nat the Presbyterian church to-\nnlirhr. TiVirlnv. nt 1 ?30 o'nlnolr Vnn\nsafety from the (grasp of the Re- are most cordially invited to hear\npuDucan poiuce uoaiu ai ivunsua himt Every member of the church\nCity. Tho \"Indians\" and the \"Rab\nbits\" are ho longer tolerated in\nMissouri politics.\nMissouri is no longer a Demo\ncratic 6tate. There are not enough j\nDemocrats to make it so. Repub- j\nlicans are in the majority. If they\nall vote the Republican ticket\nthey will win at the November\nelection and have a majority in\nthe legislature. If the .Independ\nent voters 'sustain the Republicans\nthe Democrats will eurely be de\nfeated. It is a matter, therefore,\nof getting out the lull Republi\ncan vote and Inducing independ\nent voters to vote for Republi\ncan nominees.\nis urged to be present,\nGuy B. Duff, Pastor.\nMrs. John Parsons left Wednes\nday for California.\nCLARE-SEE WEDDING.\nMr. John Clare, eon of Mr. and\nMrs. H. C. Clare, and Miss Julia\nSee, the charming and accom\nplished daughter of Mr. and Mrs.\nM. F. See of hear New Florence,\nwere united in marriage at the\nhome of the bride's parcntB Wed\nnesday evening, Oct. 12, 1910, Rev.\nTaylor Bernard of 6t. Louis of\nficiating. The wedding was a wery quiet\naffair, only the immediate rela\ntives being present.\nThe young couple will reside\nfor a time with the groom's par\nents. They have many friends in\nMontgomery county Who will ex\ntend hearty congratulations and\nbest wishes for a long and hap\npy life together.\nA. B. Lail and family aro ex\npecting to leave in a few days for\nColorado, where they will spend\nthe winter. They have \"rented their\nhome to Roy Griffith.\nThe population of Missouri in\ncreased only 6 per tent in the\npast ten years, the increase be\n.ng in St. Louis. Kansas (City and,\na few of the more prosperous\ncounties. Seventy counties lost in\npopulation. Ten (years more of\nstagnant Democratic rule twould\nhave put Missouri on tho tobog\ngan for a fear place in the pro\ngression of Astern states. The\npopulation is increasing how and\nWill continue tog row If the peo-\nprogressive executive administration.\nHADLEY SPEAKS BRIEFLY\n\"it has been a habit of tho American people,\" ho said,\n\"to settle one problem at a time, and it has been their good\nfortune to find a leader for the settlement of every problem.\n\"For the civil war the Republican party gave us Lincoln\nand Grant. After the disastrous results of the tarriff-for-rov-enue\nonly period of our history it gave us William McKlnley\nwhom we afterwards honored with tho presidency. When\nwith the return of prosperity came abuses, when commercial\nstandards became purely commercial and not moral, it gave\nto the people of this country a man who made an epoch in\nthejhistory of American politics, who demanded business sue\ncess, but who also demanded that it be lawful and honest a\nman who faced malefactors of great wealth with the same\ncourage he faced Spanish bullets on San Juan Hill and with\nwhich he went up In an aeroplane today Theodore Roose\nvelt. Extract From Hadley's Coliseum Speech\nFRANCIS, THE INSURGENT.\nIn a recent speech in Cedar\ncounty, Hon. Thos. J. Akins, in\nspeaking of alleged insurgents in i morning, Oct. 10, 1910, at 9 o'clock\nMRS. M. (E. SABIN DEAD.\nLula B. Mahler waB born in Illi\nnois June 28, 1864, and died at\nher home near this city Monday\nthe Republican party, feoid: \"The\nDemocratic party has had insurg\nents. Think of 1896 when David R.\nFrancis, who is now holding his\napron for a sweetened plum, was\na member of a president's cabi\nnet and yet left his party and\nspoke over the country for the\nticket headed by Palmer Buck\nner.\" Republicans in ?New York hon\nored Gov. Hughes, their reform\nexecutive, with a' second term,\nand the President exalted him to\na place on the Supreme bench.\nMissouri Democrats defeated their\nreformg orvernor when he asked\nfor the nomination for senator,\nandg ave that honor to a noted\noldg uard politician; and the par\nty leaders have cihee concocted\na scheme that iwill eliminate Folk\nfrom state polities' for the pres\nent, at least.\nof paralysis, aged 46 years, three\nmonths and 14 days.\nOn January 19, 1882, she was\nunited in marriage to M. E. Sabin,\nwhom she had known from child\nhood. They have Spent their en\ntire lives together, with the ex\nception of one year which she\nspent in Nebraska.\nAbout eight years ago 6he with\nher family moved from near\nPrinceton, 111., to this community.\nBy her kind disposition, and her\ndevotion to her home and fam\nily, she made many friends, who\ndeeply sympathize \"with the be\nreaved relatives.\nShe had never united with any\nchurch, but had always lived an\nupright and Christian ilife.\nShe leaves to mourn, her death',\nbesides her husband, four bons\nRoy, Clark, Jesso and Corey; five\nsisters, and her father.\nThe funeral 'services were held\nat the family residence Tuesday\nafternoon, conducted by Elder 8.\nA. Elkins, after which the remains\nwere interred in the New Flor\nence cemetery.\nCARD OF THANKS.\nWe wish to express our thanks\nto our friendB and neighbors who\nso kindly assisted us during the\nillness and death of our wife and\nmother. M. E. Sabin and Sons\nA SAFE PREDICTION.\n\"We predict that the litate Dem\nocratic central committee twill Qo\nthings this year. The signs point\nthat way.\" Palmyra Spectator,\nYes, that committee will do\nthings no doubt about that. Col.\nBill Phelps btarted .the committee\ndoing thingB when he put his erst\nwhile lobby lieutenant, Joe Shan\nnon!, at the \"helm. Everybody knows\nhow Phelps and Shannon \"do\nthings.\"\n\"In \"the long run, and inevita\nbly, the actual control of the gov\nernment will be determined by the\nchief end which the' government\nconserves.\" Roosevelt.\nDee-lightfully dee-licious, 'the\nMorse Candles. Hassler invites you\nto try them.\nTho Standard and-Free sewing!. C\nl 'ux'. r\nuiuviuxii-b, m wsnin tno market, f\nat u. aneinen'Souau anq see them\nana get prices, ana.terms,.\nFresih oysters at Hassler's Bakery.\nkkkkkkkkkkkkkkkkkkkkkkkkkk\nLyceum Lecture Entertainment Course\nLincoln McConnell; Tuesday Night Nov. 8th\nAdults $1.50 SEASON TICKETS Children 75c\nFor the Four Remaining Numbers\nLincoln McConnell j The Italian Orchestra\nA. M. Reitzel, \"Measure of a Man j\" andL the,\nHarmony Concert Co.\nThe Committee offer f pr these four spend-\nid attractions, a Season Ticket for $1.50 for\nadults